---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const repo = "https://github.com/ellisgarver/macro-narrative-dynamics";
---

<Base title="research" active="research">
  <p class="eyebrow reveal">the research</p>
  <h1 class="reveal">what this project is built on</h1>
  <p class="lede reveal">
    the idea behind the tool, the literature and work which surrounds it, and what it was built for.
  </p>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the goal</p>
    <h2>a tool for reading the recent past</h2>
    <p>
      an educational and historical-analysis tool spanning fifteen years of
      macro-financial discourse: how stories like the 2013 taper tantrum, the
      transitory-inflation debate, and the 2023 soft-landing turn emerged, took
      hold, peaked, and faded, in the words of the institutions that shaped them,
      alongside how the most recent stories are unfolding.
    </p>
    <p>
      the aim is to make an abstract idea concrete. that macro stories have
      measurable life-cycles, that you can watch one emerge, peak, and fade in the
      institutional record, is easy to state and hard to see. the tool renders the
      volume curve, switches the analytical lens, and aligns each narrative against
      market series for direct comparison.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the idea</p>
    <h2>the narrative-economics idea</h2>

    <figure class="idea-graphic reveal">
      <svg class="contagion" viewBox="0 0 320 130" aria-hidden="true">
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="120" y2="30" />
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="130" y2="100" />
        <line class="edge" x1="120" y1="30" x2="200" y2="42" />
        <line class="edge" x1="130" y1="100" x2="210" y2="92" />
        <line class="edge" x1="200" y1="42" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <line class="edge" x1="210" y1="92" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <circle class="node n-s" cx="60" cy="65" r="9" />
        <circle class="node n-a" cx="120" cy="30" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-b" cx="130" cy="100" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-c" cx="200" cy="42" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-d" cx="210" cy="92" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-e" cx="270" cy="65" r="9" />
      </svg>
      <figcaption class="sir-key">
        <span><i class="dot s"></i>hasn't heard it</span>
        <span><i class="dot i"></i>carrying it</span>
        <span><i class="dot r"></i>moved on</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      the starting point is Robert Shiller's <em>Narrative Economics</em> (2017 AEA
      presidential address; 2019 book): economic stories spread through a population
      the way contagious ideas do: a story is picked up, carried for a while, and
      eventually dropped. the stories people carry shape the economic decisions
      they make, so what spreads matters as much as the fundamentals.
    </p>
    <p>
      this tool takes the measurable part of that idea, that narratives have
      life-cycles, and reads them directly from the record:
      each stage comes straight from the volume trajectory of institutional macro
      writing, model-free, so no reading depends on any one theory of how stories
      spread being right. the contagion picture above survives as one of three
      interpretive lenses fit alongside (epidemic, growth, and adoption curves),
      each a different account of the same measured shape, shown with how well
      it fits and never used to decide the stage.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the grounding</p>
    <h2>field-standard parameters</h2>
    <p>
      every parameter in the pipeline is a published library default or a value
      taken from the primary literature with a citation. all of them live in a
      single configuration file, and every random step flows from one fixed seed.
      where no field-accepted anchor exists, the parameter is removed, and no
      parameter is ever adjusted to make the output look better.
    </p>
    <p>
      the press and markets overlays on each narrative are display layers only.
      neither is an input to the embedding, the clustering, or the curve fits.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      see the full methodology, with citations in
      <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/METHODOLOGY.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">METHODOLOGY.md</a>
      from the repository.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">further reading</p>
    <h2>references &amp; related work</h2>
    <ul class="reading">
      <li>Andre et al. (2025). “Narratives about the Macroeconomy.” <em>Review of Economic Studies</em>, advance article.</li>
      <li>Ash &amp; Hansen (2023). “Text Algorithms in Economics.” <em>Annual Review of Economics</em>, 15, 659–688.</li>
      <li>Baker et al. (2016). “Measuring Economic Policy Uncertainty.” <em>Quarterly Journal of Economics</em>, 131(4), 1593–1636.</li>
      <li>Bass (1969). “A New Product Growth for Model Consumer Durables.” <em>Management Science</em>, 15(5), 215–227.</li>
      <li>Bertsch et al. (2021). “Narrative Fragmentation and the Business Cycle.” <em>Economics Letters</em>, 201, 109783.</li>
      <li>Bybee et al. (2024). “Business News and Business Cycles.” <em>Journal of Finance</em>, 79(5), 3105–3147.</li>
      <li>Daley &amp; Kendall (1965). “Stochastic Rumours.” <em>J. Inst. Maths Applics</em>, 1(1), 42–55.</li>
      <li>de Jesus &amp; da Nóbrega Besarria (2025). “Central Bank Narratives and Macroeconomic Forecasting.” <em>IMF Economic Review</em>.</li>
      <li>Flynn &amp; Sastry (2024). “The Macroeconomics of Narratives.” NBER Working Paper 32602.</li>
      <li>Gentzkow et al. (2019). “Text as Data.” <em>Journal of Economic Literature</em>, 57(3), 535–574.</li>
      <li>Goffman &amp; Newill (1964). “Generalization of Epidemic Theory.” <em>Nature</em>, 204, 225–228.</li>
      <li>Grootendorst (2022). “BERTopic: Neural Topic Modeling with a Class-Based TF-IDF Procedure.” arXiv:2203.05794.</li>
      <li>Gueta et al. (2025). “Can LLMs Learn Macroeconomic Narratives from Social Media?” <em>Findings of NAACL 2025</em>.</li>
      <li>Hansen et al. (2018). “Transparency and Deliberation within the FOMC.” <em>Quarterly Journal of Economics</em>, 133(2), 801–870.</li>
      <li>Kermack &amp; McKendrick (1927). “A Contribution to the Mathematical Theory of Epidemics.” <em>Proc. R. Soc. A</em>, 115, 700–721.</li>
      <li>Larsen &amp; Thorsrud (2019). “The Value of News for Economic Developments.” <em>Journal of Econometrics</em>, 210(1), 203–218.</li>
      <li>Larsen et al. (2021). “News-Driven Inflation Expectations and Information Rigidities.” <em>Journal of Monetary Economics</em>, 117, 507–520.</li>
      <li>Roos &amp; Reccius (2024). “Narratives in Economics.” <em>Journal of Economic Surveys</em>, 38(2), 303–341.</li>
      <li>Schmidt et al. (2025). “Identifying Economic Narratives in Large Text Corpora Using Large Language Models.” arXiv:2506.15041.</li>
      <li>Shiller (2017). “Narrative Economics.” <em>American Economic Review</em>, 107(4), 967–1004.</li>
      <li>Shiller (2019). <em>Narrative Economics: How Stories Go Viral and Drive Major Economic Events</em>. Princeton University Press.</li>
      <li>Tetlock (2007). “Giving Content to Investor Sentiment.” <em>Journal of Finance</em>, 62(3), 1139–1168.</li>
      <li>Verhulst (1838). “Notice sur la loi que la population suit dans son accroissement.” <em>Corresp. Math. Phys.</em>, 10, 113–121.</li>
      <li>Project documentation: <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/METHODOLOGY.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">METHODOLOGY.md</a> and <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/related_work.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">related_work.md</a>.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* contagion motif: a small SIR spread that loops — one seed infects its
     neighbours, then everyone recovers. */
  .idea-graphic { margin: 1.2rem auto 1.4rem; max-width: 340px; text-align: center; }
  .contagion { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
  .edge { stroke: var(--line); stroke-width: 1.4; opacity: 0.5; }
  .node { fill: var(--faint); animation: infect 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }
  @keyframes infect {
    0%, 8% { fill: var(--faint); }
    20% { fill: var(--ember); }
    42% { fill: var(--ember); }
    60%, 92% { fill: var(--growth); }
    100% { fill: var(--faint); }
  }
  .n-s { animation-delay: 0s; } .n-a { animation-delay: 0.7s; } .n-b { animation-delay: 0.9s; }
  .n-c { animation-delay: 1.5s; } .n-d { animation-delay: 1.7s; } .n-e { animation-delay: 2.4s; }
  .sir-key {
    display: flex; gap: 1.1rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 0.5rem; color: var(--muted); font-size: var(--fs-meta);
  }
  .sir-key span { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.35rem; }
  .sir-key .dot { width: 0.6rem; height: 0.6rem; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; }
  .sir-key .s { background: var(--faint); }
  .sir-key .i { background: var(--ember); }
  .sir-key .r { background: var(--growth); }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .node { animation: none; fill: var(--growth); }
  }

  .reading {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 1.1rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
  }
  .reading li {
    padding: 0.6rem 0 0.6rem 1.6rem;
    text-indent: -1.6rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .reading li:first-child { border-top: none; }
  .reading a { color: var(--decay); }
</style>
